243	Suspects in Nemtsov killing probably tortured - Russian rights activist
338	Three suspects in the killing of Russian opposition leader Boris Nemtsov have
416	probably been tortured while in detention, a member of the Kremlin's advisory
494	council on human rights said on Wednesday.
546	After visiting three of the five ethnic Chechen suspects at Moscow's Lefortovo
625	prison as part of a monitoring group, rights activist Andrey Babushkin said
701	the men detained over the Feb. 27 murder had suffered multiple injuries.
783	Nemtsov was the most prominent of a string of Kremlin critics to be killed
858	during President Vladimir Putin's 15-year rule. The brazen shooting in the
933	heart of Moscow has shocked his colleagues and supporters, who say the
1004	investigation is a test of the rule of law in Russia.
1067	A Russian judge has said former Chechen policeman Zaur Dadayev, who is being
1144	held along with his cousins, Anzor and Shagid Gubashev, has admitted
1213	involvement in the murder. Dadayev and Anzor Gubashev have been formally
1286	charged.
1304	"There are reasonable grounds to believe that Dadayev and the Gubashevs were
1381	tortured," Babushkin wrote on his website.
1433	He said Dadayev had "multiple injuries" visible on his body, while Anzor
1506	Gubashev had abrasions around his nose, wrists and legs that were incurred
1581	after he was detained.
1613	In a conversation with Babushkin, Dadayev said he had only admitted his guilt
1691	after being promised that the authorities would then free his friend Rustam
1767	Yusupov, who was detained at the same time.
1820	"They said if I confess, they would let him out. I agreed. I thought that I
1896	would save him and they would take me to Moscow alive," he said according to a
1975	transcript published in Moskovsky Komsomolets newspaper, whose reporter was
2051	present during the visit.
